  "prompt": "What is an acid, base, and pH?",
  "response": "Let me explain acids, bases, and pH:\n\nAcids:\n- Substances that donate hydrogen ions (H+) when dissolved in water\n- Taste sour\n- React with metals\n- Have a pH less than 7\n- Examples: hydrochloric acid, citric acid, vinegar\n\nBases:\n- Substances that accept hydrogen ions or donate hydroxide ions (OH-) when dissolved in water\n- Taste bitter\n- Feel slippery\n- React with acids to neutralize them\n- Have a pH greater than 7\n- Examples: sodium hydroxide, ammonia, baking soda\n\npH:\n- Stands for \"potential of hydrogen\"\n- Measures the concentration of hydrogen ions in a solution\n- Ranges from 0 to 14\n- Neutral pH is 7\n- pH < 7 is acidic\n- pH > 7 is basic/alkaline\n- Each pH unit represents a 10-fold change in hydrogen ion concentration\n- Measured using pH paper, litmus paper, or pH meters\n\npH Scale Examples:\n- 0: Very strong acid (battery acid)\n- 7: Neutral (pure water)\n- 14: Very strong base (drain cleaner)",
